<p>Element, as chemist knows, is substance that cannot be chemically interconverted or broken down into simpler substances 
and are primary constituents of matter. Ancient simply identify them as earth, water, air and fire. Natural abundance of iron, gold, silver, lead, 
tin, mercury, sulfur and carbon, are the very first known elements, used to build civilization. Other elements are hiding in mixture 
or compounds, and could not easily extracted or purified them. Early chemist classified them by its properties and characteristic,
subsequently discover many more ( and the way to purify and extract, even now synthesis them ), with nearly all of the naturally-occuring elements becoming known
by 1900.</p> 
<p>One man, sheds light on, <strong>to sort</strong> known elements at that time with numbers in a table-ordered. 
<strong>Dmitri Ivanovich Mendeleev</strong> ( Russian, Дми́трий Ива́нович Менделе́ев, 1834-1907 ), in 1869, published his formulation to correct the properties of 
some already discovered elements and also to predict the properties of elements yet to be discovered. This work, as we know it as, the <strong>Periodic Table of Elements</strong>.
</p>
<div>
    <img title="Periodic Table" src="{{ MEDIA }}periodic_table.svg" style="width: 99%;">
    <div class="credit">
    <span>Source: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_table">wikipedia</a></span>
    </div>
</div>
<div>
    <h3>Periodicity Of Elements</h3><br>
    The essential model, or theory to understand element's chemical properties came from the early birth of quantum mechanics, known as electron configuration.
    Element is modeled as <em>atom</em> with its "number", the <em>atomic number</em> <strong>( Z )</strong> that contains number of protons, therefore same number of electrons in ground state. 
    And the periodicity of elements might be explained by the <em>electron structure of the atom</em>, and best explained in the quantum theory.<br>
    <br>
    An electron in the atom can now be completely specified by the four quantum members:<br><br>
    <ul style="margin-left: 10%;">
        <li>n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=&nbsp;the principal quantum number( or simply, <em>quantum number</em> ), e.g: 1,2,3&#133;</li>
        <li>ℓ&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=&nbsp;the orbital quantum number( or simply, <em>angular number</em> ), e.g: 0,1,2&#133;</li>
        <li>m<sub>l</sub>&nbsp;&nbsp;=&nbsp;the orbital magnetic quantum number( or simply, <em>magnetic number</em> ), e.g: -2,-1,0,+1,+2&#133;</li>
        <li>m<sub>s</sub>&nbsp;&nbsp;=&nbsp;the spin magnetic quantum number( or simply, <em>spin number</em> ), e.g: &#x207A;&#189; or &#x207B;&#189;.</li>
    </ul>
    The four quantum members designate <strong>specific levels, orbitals, magnetics, and spins of electrons</strong>. This explains that they are describing 
    in detail the characteristic of the electrons in the atom. The <em>principal quantum number n</em> describes the energy level of the electron shell. When value of 
    the n is higher, the number of principal electron shell is greater, means a greater distance between the farthest electron and its nucleus. 
    As a result, size and radius of the atom increases. The <em>angular quantum number l</em> describes the shape of the orbital. <strong>Each quantum number</strong> is composed of 
    one or more subshells( orbital ). The detail of possible subshells are shown in following table:<br>
    <br>
    <table class="orbital-quantum">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Orbital label</th>
                <th><i>&nbsp;ℓ&nbsp;</i></th>
                <th>Max electrons</th>
                <th>Spectroscopic Name</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td class="center">s</td>
